<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-08-01T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-08-01T03:00:00-05:00" n="571" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d571">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115 Standard Vacuum Oil Company/43:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-08-01T16:00:00+08:00">August 1, 1938—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received August 1—7 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>329. Peiping’s 478, July 31, noon. I believe it would be advisable to
                            authorize the placing of a marine guard on the British tug as it appears
                            that unless this is done the American cargo in question will be unable
                            to reach Tientsin.</p>
                        <p>I presume Department will issue appropriate instructions to Peiping.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>